The Meru clergy has said it will not condone hooliganism, electoral malpractice and hate speech that may trigger violence in the August polls. The Meru County Ministers Forum patron, Edward Buria, on Monday said the church has taken note of the recent political chaos where acts of hooliganism and hate speech have been reported.&ldquo;We have heard divisive utterances by politicians. The church will not allow any politician to divide the people of Meru through divisive politics,&rdquo; Buria said. He urged police and other security agencies to question politicians spreading hate.